		  <td class="forum_boardrow1" style="border-width: 0px 1px 1px 1px;" valign="top"><div id="message30802865">I disagree with Romario3210's assessment that the first arc is bad.  (I feel also I should note in the interest of full disclosure that I have not viewed the entire series—I'm viewing it several episodes per week with a local anime club—so many of my remarks will be based on my experience with the manga, however I believe this should be mostly valid for purposes of this discussion since all of my remarks are concerned with the story rather than visual aspects of the production.)<br />
<br />
Whether or not you will enjoy the first arc of JJBA (Phantom Blood) largely comes down to a single question: can you stomach melodrama?  Because Phantom Blood is deeply melodramatic.<br />
<br />
For the sake of clarification, melodramatic does not mean "sad."  By the book, it's defined as "exaggerated and emotional or sentimental; sensational or sensationalized; overdramatic."  And Phantom Blood is all of the above.  None of the characters are nuanced; every character is defined by a single trait which is exaggerated to the most epic of proportions.  Jonathan Joestar is heroic, and nothing but heroic, all the time, from the moment we first see him.  Dio is evil, and nothing but evil, all the time, from the moment we first see him.<br />
<br />
I would contend that melodrama is not inherently bad, though many people who apply one set of storytelling criteria to every work they view will likely have problems with melodramatic storytelling.<br />
<br />
I tremendously enjoyed Phantom Blood precisely because of its melodrama.  I believe that fundamentally, all storytelling is about making and fulfilling promises, and what better way to make and deliver on promises by having every character operate along a single axis?  From the very beginning when we see Dio established as an evil person when he literally kicks the dog, the audience is primed to see Dio evolve into a powerful villain, and seeing him don the mask is the ultimate fulfillment of this.  Similarly, Jonathan's chivalry manifests itself very early on, and we see the ultimate payoff when JoJo is virtuous almost to a fault.  (For example, the part where he goes on a research trip to determine whether his father is actually being poisoned, when he has every reason to believe that foul play is afoot.)  From the very beginning of the story, we are made promises about who the major actors will be, what their roles will be, and what the central conflict will be (the mask is the actually the first piece of the story we're introduced to).<br />
<br />
Perhaps adding to my enjoyment of the melodrama is the setting, which I think fits the tone incredibly well.  The thought at the top of my mind as I read Phantom Blood was, "If graphic novels existed in the 19th century, this is what they would have looked like."  And from that standpoint, I found it tremendously enjoyable to explore a narrative that, by its nature, is completely bombastic.  Not every work needs to be subtle and nuanced.  Phantom Blood lays all of its cards down on the table very early, and you can count on getting exactly what you'd expect based on its early development.<br />
<br />
As a bit of an aside, I think that one common trait that can be seen in many of the Japanese works that have large fan followings on tumblr (JJBA being one of them) is that they tend to share melodramatic traits.  For example, Attack on Titan is incredibly melodramatic.  Visual novels like Ace Attorney and Dangan Ronpa are similarly exaggerated in the way that it does characterization. The same is true of Madoka to a lesser extent.</div><div class="postActions"></div></td>
		</tr></table></div><div class="forum_boardrowspacer">&nbsp;</div>
