		  <td width="135" class="forum_boardrow2" style="border-width: 0px 0px 1px 1px;" valign="top"><div id="messageuser31488515" style="padding-bottom: 2px;"><a href="/profile/Lindle"><strong>Lindle</strong></a></div>
		  
		  <a href="/profile/Lindle"><img src="http://cdn.myanimelist.net/images/useravatars/232951.gif" vspace="2" border="0"></a>
		  <br>
		  Offline<br>
		  Joined: Sep 2009<br>
		  Posts: 2813
		  </td>
		  <td class="forum_boardrow1" style="border-width: 0px 1px 1px 1px;" valign="top"><div id="message31488515">Someone on the JJBA Facebook group just posted this and I feel like it deserves to be here.<br />
<br />
&quot;Part Three (so far. I'm at Mariah and Bast) is full of interesting characters with cool powers and whatnot. The cast, the setting, and the scope of the manga are all much more varied and expansive that Part Two. This was probably good for Araki as a writer, and it's amazing to see how well he can command such a varied group of characters.<br />
<br />
Part Two has a smaller cast and a similarly spread-out setting, but just not the range that Part Three boasts. Joseph's adventure certainly takes him to an interesting mix of locations, but Part Three was more varied and their places were more distinct. Also, Part Two's cast is not as strong (in numbers and fighting ability) as Part Three's. Jotaro and friends is about the group's march against Dio and his proxies while Joseph's adventure is a more focused struggle. Joseph is the obvious star of Part Two while Jotaro shares the limelight with the rest of the regulars.<br />
<br />
Though I agree that Part Three is more ambitious than Part Two, I personally feel that this ambition is the main reason that Part Two is superior. In Part Three, Araki creates a true manga hero. Jotaro mysteriously obtains gargantuan power with no training and proceeds to kick everyone's ass in a brooding but pure-hearted fashion (if that doesn't scream MANGA PROTAGONIST, I don't know what does). Star Platinum seems practically invincible at this point! Part Two's hero was always the underdog. He wins all his battles by the skin of his teeth. Each encounter may be his last. Joseph's every victory is a true victory in that he really had to bleed for it. He always surprises you in the end, making you laugh with relief as you see that somehow, once again, he has made it out alive. Jotaro barely ever seems like he is in any danger. In Part Two, we are rooting for the unpopular bet. In Part Three, we are betting on the obvious smart choice. There is a reason that one wins exponentially higher earnings when a dark horse or an underdog comes out of nowhere and steals the race. I'd rather root for a David than a Goliath any day.<br />
<br />
Also, speaking of Goliaths, the villains in Part Two are stronger characters that Part Three's slew of gimmick characters. Jotaro and crew go from dreading every next battle to laughing in the faces of their aggressors after they've emerged victorious. Part Three's villains go from terrifying to ridiculous. One battle in Part Three only shows us the stand user for one panel! No noble speeches out of these cannon fodder, just comic relief. When the villains in Part Two showed up, it was always a big deal. That trio of titans truly struck fear into the protagonists' hearts because they had a noble terror to them. We gain a real appreciation of the three's power and personalities. Also, the three villains aren't just evil, they're respectable warriors in their own right. There is a mutual respect between combatants in Part Two, while Part Three has more taunting and bravado. This gives the deaths in Part Two a solemn weight that was lacking in Part Three. Part Two's death scenes were Shakespearean in their dignity. In some cases, Part Three's deaths or defeats were downright Adam-Sandler levels of slapstick. In Part Two, each fight is a real and weighty clash of warriors. In Part Three, a large chunk of the battles felt like filler material.<br />
<br />
That's the main difference between the two in my mind. Part Two is a stronger story than Part Three. Though Joseph was certainly more of a ham than Jotaro, Part Two felt more grand, more serious, and inspired deeper terror, deeper admiration, and an overall better experience. Though Jotaro and the crew take themselves more seriously than Joseph ever did, Part Three feels more drawn out and less important than Part Two. Battle Tendency is nearer to my heart than Stardust Crusaders will ever be.&quot;</div><div class="postActions"></div><div class="sig"><img class="userimg" data-src="http://i.imgur.com/Y1FB912.png" /><br />
<span style="font-size: 150%;"><!--link--><a href="http://theotaku2anime.wordpress.com/2014/04/28/joe-the-lion-crackpot-jojolion-theory-time/#more-1192" rel="nofollow">Latest Blog: Joe The Lion - Crackpot JoJolion Theory Time!</a></div></td>
		</tr></table></div><div class="forum_boardrowspacer">&nbsp;</div>
